&lt;h1 id="learn-the-power-of-other-mathematicians-tools"&gt;Learn the power of other mathematicians&amp;rsquo; tools&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I suppose it is tempting, if the only tool you have is a hammer, to treat everything as if it were a nail.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;— Abraham Maslow, &amp;ldquo;Psychology of Science&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;You will find, when listening to talks or reading papers, that there will be problems which interest you which were solved using an unfamiliar tool, but seem &lt;strong&gt;out of reach of your own personal &amp;ldquo;bag of tricks&amp;rdquo;&lt;/strong&gt;. When this happens, you should try to see whether your own tools can in fact accomplish a similar task, but you should also try to work out what made the other tool so effective – for instance, to locate the simplest model case in which that tool does something non-trivial.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item><item><title>Don’t be afraid to learn things outside your field</title><link>https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/orig/dont-be-afraid-to-learn-things-outside-your-field/</link><pubDate>Sun, 06 May 2007 18:55:51 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/orig/dont-be-afraid-to-learn-things-outside-your-field/</guid><description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://linguista.cn/terencetao/career-advice/zh/dont-be-afraid-to-learn-things-outside-your-field.zh/"&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;
